 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK| 

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Local><Name>recSel</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeSelection</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local></Method><Method><Name>ResetLastInfo</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Resets the last information

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize></Method><Method><Name>ReadAndSaveRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Reads the current PLC values into the recipe and afterwards stores the recipe into the standard recipe file

 The content of an existing file will be overridden.

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_SAVE_ERR|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>GetRecipeVariableNames</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Returns the recipe variable names from the corresponding recipe

 **Example:**

 We have 50 recipe variable names. We want to create a table which shows 10 recipe variable names at the same time.
 We define a string array ``strArr: ARRAY[0..9] OF STRING;``
 Corresponding to the ``iStartIndex`` we can get the recipe variable names from a specific area.

 	- ``StartIndex`` := 0; The variable names 0..9 are returned.
 	- ``iStartIndex`` := 20; The variable names 20..29 are returned.

 In this example:

 	- ``iSize`` := 10;
 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe definition. ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe. ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>pStrings</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ The strings where the recipe values should be stored ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><ArrayInfo PointerTo="1"><LBound>0</LBound><Elements>1</Elements></ArrayInfo><BitSize>64</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iSize</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Size of the string array. ]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iStartIndex</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Start index. Can be used for a scrolling function (See example)]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>ReadRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Reads the current PLC values into the recipe

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|
		- DataServer Errors from 16#2000 to 16#20FF, 
		- DataSourceDriver Errors from 16#2100 to 16#21FF

 DataServer and DataSourceDriver errors can occur if a DataServer and DataSource is configured beneth your current application (CODESYS HMI) and the command
 is called from the visualization.

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Local><Name>recSel</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeSelection</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local></Method><Method><Name>LoadAndWriteRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Loads a recipe from the standard recipe file and afterwards writes the recipe into the PLC variables

 .. note::
    Entries in the recipe that do not include value assignments are not loaded and written. 
    Refer to the "Load and write Recipe" command.

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_FILE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_MISMATCH|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_ALL_VARIABLES_WERE_LOADED|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.
]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>SaveRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Stores the recipe into the standard recipe file

 The content of an existing file will be overridden.
 The standard recipe file name is ``<recipe>.<recipedefinition>.<recipeextension>``.

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_SAVE_ERR|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Local><Name>recSel</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeSelection</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local></Method><Method><Name>CreateRecipeNoSave</Name><Comment><![CDATA[  Creates a new recipe in the specified recipe definition and afterwared reads the current PLC values into the new recipe

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_ALREADY_EXIST|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOMEMORY|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>ResetLastError</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Resets the last error

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize></Method><Method><Name>WriteRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Writes the recipe into the PLC variables

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Local><Name>recSel</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeSelection</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local></Method><Method><Name>GetRecipeValues</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Returns the recipe values from the corresponding recipe.

 **Example:**

 We have 50 recipe values. We want to create a table which shows 10 recipe values at the same time.
 We define a string array ``strArr: ARRAY[0..9] OF STRING;``
 Corresponding to the ``iStartIndex`` we can get the recipe values from a specific area.

 	- ``iStartIndex`` := 0; The values 0..9 are returned.
 	- ``iStartIndex`` := 20; The values 20..29 are returned.

 In this example:

 	- ``iStringLength`` := 80; The default STRING has 80 characters.
 	- ``iSize`` := 10;
 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe definition. ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe. ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>pStrings</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ The strings where the recipe values should be stored. ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><ArrayInfo PointerTo="1"><LBound>0</LBound><Elements>1</Elements></ArrayInfo><BitSize>64</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iSize</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Size of the string array. ]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iStartIndex</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Start index. Can be used for a scrolling function. (See example). ]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iStringLength</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Length of a string in the pStrings array. It should correspond to the actual amount of characters. ]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>GetRecipeNames</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Returns the recipe names from the corresponding recipe definition

 **Example:**

 We have 50 recipes. We want to create a table which shows 10 recipe names at the same time.
 We define a string array ``strArr: ARRAY[0..9] OF STRING``;

 Corresponding to the ``iStartIndex`` we can get the recipe names from a specific area.

 	- ``StartIndex`` := 0; The names 0..9 are returned.
 	- ``iStartIndex`` := 20; The names 20..29 are returned.

 In this example:

 	- ``iSize`` := 10;
 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>pStrings</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ The strings were the recipe values should be stored ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><ArrayInfo PointerTo="1"><LBound>0</LBound><Elements>1</Elements></ArrayInfo><BitSize>64</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iSize</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Size of the string array ]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iStartIndex</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Start index. Can be used for a scrolling function (see example)]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>LoadRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Loads a recipe from the standard recipe file

 The standard recipe file name is ``<recipe>.<recipedefinition>.<recipeextension>``.

 .. note::
    Entries in the recipe that do not include value assignments are not loaded and written. 
    Refer to the "Load and write Recipe" command.

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_FILE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_MISMATCH|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_ALL_VARIABLES_WERE_LOADED|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Local><Name>recSel</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeSelection</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local></Method><Method><Name>LoadFromAndWriteRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Loads a recipe from the specified recipe file and afterwards writes the recipe into the PLC variables


 .. note::
    Entries in the recipe that do not include value assignments are not loaded and written. 
    Refer to the "Load and write Recipe" command.

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_FILE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_MISMATCH|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_ALL_VARIABLES_WERE_LOADED|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.

]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe definition. ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe. ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>FileName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the file ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(255)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Local><Name>recipeDefinition</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeDefinition</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local><Local><Name>pPersistentRecipeHelper</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management" PointerTo="1">IPersistentRecipeHelper</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local><Local><Name>recSel</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeSelection</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local></Method><Method><Name>RegisterDatasourceRecipeDefinition</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Helper method that can be used to preregister variable lists for a recipe definition within devices connected via datasources.
 The intention of this function is to speedup reading/writing of recipes at the cost of an initial registration process
 after each connection setup of the affected datasources. If a recipe is read or written several times then this initial effort 
 is necessary only once and each read or write operation is executed faster.
 
 .. important:: 
 	This functionality does not automatically update the created variable list in case of online changes (eg. affecting the recipe definition). 
 	Therefore if online changes modify a recipe definition or locations of variables within a recipe definition, the
 	according list has to be setup again! This can be done by searching and deleting it using the methodes of |IDatasources.IDatasourcesMgr2|
 
 .. important:: 
 	This function might block until it is possible to access the datasources.

 .. note:: 
 	If there is no performance flaw when reading/writing recipe definitions over datasources then it's not necessary to call this method. 
 
 .. note:: 
 	The error code |CmpErrors.Errors.ERR_NOT_SUPPORTED| signals that one of the affected datasources does not support 
 	this feature and so it cannot be used at all.
 	The error code |IDatasources.Errors.ERR_DS_READONLY_ITEM| signals that at least one of the variables of the recipe definition is reaonly
 	and therefore the feature of preregistering according variable lists is not supported.
 
 :return: An error code representing the result of this operation.
 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe definition. ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>datasourcesMgr</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ The global instance of the datasources manager. Typically pass g_Datasources ]]></Comment><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management.IDatasources">IDatasourcesMgr</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Parameter><Local><Name>recDef</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeDefinition</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local><Local><Name>dsMgr2</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management.IDatasources">IDatasourcesMgr2</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local><Local><Name>i</Name><Type>DINT</Type><BitSize>32</BitSize></Local><Local><Name>itemsList</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management.IDatasources">IDataItemListPersistant</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local><Local><Name>recDef2</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeDefinition2</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local><Local><Name>varsCount</Name><Type>DINT</Type><BitSize>32</BitSize></Local><Local><Name>pVarName</Name><Type PointerTo="1">BYTE</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local></Method><Method><Name>SetRecipeValues</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Sets the recipe values of the corresponding recipe

 **Example:**

 We have 50 recipe values. We want to create a table which sets 10 recipe values at the same time.
 We define a string array ``strArr: ARRAY[0..9] OF STRING;``
 Corresponding to the ``iStartIndex`` we can set the recipe values from a specific area.

 	- ``StartIndex`` := 0; The values 0..9 are set.
 	- ``iStartIndex`` := 20; The values 20..29 are set.

 In this example:
 	- ``iSize`` := 10;
 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>pStrings</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ The strings with the recipe values ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><ArrayInfo PointerTo="1"><LBound>0</LBound><Elements>1</Elements></ArrayInfo><BitSize>64</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iSize</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Size of the string array. ]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iStartIndex</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Start index. Can be used for a scrolling function (see example)]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>ReadAndSaveAs</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Reads the current PLC values and stores the values in a recipe file without changing any existing recipe

 The content of an existing file will be overridden.

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_SAVE_ERR|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe definition. ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter><Parameter><Name>FileName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the file ]]></Comment><Type ReferenceTo="true">STRING(255)</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize><Properties><Property><Name>ItemType</Name><Value>InOut</Value></Property></Properties></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>GetRecipeCount</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Returns the recipe count of the corresponding recipe definition

